Imagine you're an inspector for a company that uses a software as a vital tool for landowners to measure the boundaries of their properties. You've been tasked with reviewing a new design for this software that includes a specific feature-locking mechanism. In this assessment, you're asked to analyze the diagram below, an architect's design for a house with a rectangular backyard, which is surrounded by a garden featuring a few flowerbeds, walkways, and decorative rocks.

 [asy]
defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
draw((0,0)--(0,5)--(8,5)--(8,0)--cycle);
draw((0,3)--(8,3));
draw((6,5)--(6,0));
[/asy]

Notice that the two rectangles in the diagram have different heights. Now, you start examining the garden closely. You notice that the designer of the house might have used these rectangles to achieve a specific design requirement.

What you need to determine is how many different types of rectangles are present in this garden design, considering the dimensions and properties of the rectangles. To do this, you'll need to analyze the rectangles more closely.

