 Imagine you're a mathematician and your friend, a brilliant scientist, wants to tell you about a fascinating concept in geometry. The concept is about how the area of a quadrilateral can be determined by understanding the relationships between its sides and angles. Your friend gives you a diagram showing a quadrilateral XYZW:

[asy]
size(200);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
pair X = (0,0), Y = 96*dir(45), Z = (Y.x + 32, Y.y), W = (Z.x,Z.y - 24);
draw(X--Y--Z--W--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(Y,Z,W,100));
label("$X$",X,SW);
label("$Y$",Y,NW);
label("$Z$",Z,NE);
label("$W$",W,SE);
label("96",X--Y,NW);
label("104",X--W,SE);
label("24",Z--W,E);
label("32",Y--Z,N);
[/asy]

Your friend mentions that this problem is a great example of how understanding the properties of particular quadrilaterals can lead to deeper insights in geometry. Your friend asks you to explain the steps to find the area of XYZW. Can you describe the process and calculate the area? The formula you'll develop will be useful when tackling various problems involving quadrilaterals in the future.

